# Firm Permissions Policy (TEMPLATE)

> Copy this file to `protocols/permissions.md` in your firm's config
> directory. Edit to match your scope model + employee roster. The
> parser reads `## firm:`, `## default_scope:` (optional), and the
> individual `### scope:` / `### employee:` sections. Comments and free
> text between sections are ignored.

## firm: acme-capital

## default_scope: public

---

## Scopes

### scope: public

Baseline scope every employee has implicitly. Use for firm info that
is safe to share across the whole team — employee roster, publicly
stated firm thesis, industry memos, generic research.

### scope: partner-only

Partner-level strategy: deal pipeline specifics, portfolio construction
notes, LP communications, compensation discussions. Not visible to
associates or analysts.

### scope: client-confidential

Client-specific PII + account details + bespoke preferences. Only
employees directly servicing that client see these pages.

### scope: deal-team

Deal-specific working notes + negotiation state. Members rotate per
deal; scope is per-firm but membership is expected to churn.

---

## Employees

### employee: alice

scopes: [public, partner-only, deal-team]

### employee: bob

scopes: [public, deal-team]

### employee: carol

scopes: [public]

---

## Notes for administrators

- **Adding a scope:** insert a new `### scope: <name>` heading + a short
  description. Then grant it to the relevant employees.
- **Promoting an employee:** add the higher-privilege scope name to
  their `scopes: [...]` list. No need to restart anything — the policy
  file is read on each session boot.
- **Removing access:** delete the scope from the employee's list. Any
  firm-plane page tagged with that scope becomes unreadable for them
  on the next retrieval.
- **Default deny:** employees not listed in this file have NO access
  beyond `public`. Keep the file current.
- **Scope on pages:** firm-plane pages add `scope: <name>` to their
  YAML frontmatter. Pages without a scope fall back to
  `default_scope` above.
- **No-escalation rule:** `can_propose(employee, scope)` returns True
  only when the employee already has read access to that scope. An
  associate cannot propose a `partner-only` promotion even if they've
  somehow read the source material.
